<Base title="User Stories" description="User stories – meaningful user narratives by Hob by Horse.">
<div class="lp"><section class="hero"><div class="hi">
<p class="kicker">Strategy</p>
<h1>User Stories – Meaningful User Narratives</h1>
<p>With every entry of a search term and every subsequent click, users tell valuable user stories about the shopping experience in your online shop. This makes it possible to describe the functionalities of your shop system from the customer's perspective. We use the strengths and weaknesses from these experiences for your digital project management and development improvements tailored to your individual business model.</p>
</div></section>
<div class="content">
<h2>User Stories – Tools for Website Development by Hob by Horse</h2>
<p>User stories answer the core questions of who, what and why. Who are the visitors to your online shop. What describes the products, services and information sought. Behind the why lies the motivation for the respective search. From this we develop roles for wishes regarding functionality, aligned with the goal of every internet search.</p>
<h2>Example Elements of a User Story</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Story templates:</strong> They correspond to different customer expectations according to industry and search relevance for your online shop in the question principle described above. The end of the sentence always captures the reason for the search and thus your potential for optimisations.</li>
<li><strong>User story effort:</strong> This is estimated before writing begins either in person-days or according to required story points. Criteria and links, the total size and structural features of architecture components needed for the story are also calculated.</li>
<li><strong>Acceptance criteria:</strong> The more optimally your online shop corresponds to the search motivation of the target group, the more likely this target group will accept advertising offers, calls to action and service components.</li>
<li><strong>Splitting:</strong> User stories are project work, divided among several team members. For this, they are split into small project goals, each of which one involved person is responsible for. Afterwards, the assembled details create the overall picture of the users.</li>
</ul>
<p>As a development team, we know various variants for a user story according to principles such as INVEST or DEEP as well as dependencies to other user stories. Creating them as an ongoing service is necessary, as markets, industries and user expectations are in constant change in digital commerce.</p>
<h2>User Stories – as Diverse as Industry Users</h2>
<p>Companies in research and development create completely different user stories than retailers in fashion or lifestyle. Machine manufacturers expect different application criteria than the end customers of their technologies. The tourism, hospitality and gastronomy industries, food producers, traders and processors, or service providers from fitness, insurance and real estate are also in constant trend change.</p>
<h2>User Stories Developed by Hob by Horse for a Precisely Defined Target Group</h2>
<p>Above all, splitting user stories makes it possible to target different audience groups. B2B traders tell of their shopping experience, B2C consumers of fashion items, readers of magazines or enthusiastic cinema-goers. D2C manufacturers often experience competition from online shops of intermediaries. For the A2A and A2C target group of authorities and institutions, price aspects and glittering advertising campaigns play at most a secondary role.</p>
<p><em>Contact Hob by Horse by telephone or <a href="mailto:info@hob-by-horse.de">email</a> for unique, precise user stories of high relevance for the target groups of all industries!</em></p>
</div></div>
